segments.text: That was at the Journal of the American Society, I mean the American Society... American Medical Association, in the ophthalmology section.
Uh-huh.
And that's where you made your first major defense in your... Well, yeah, except in the literature now.
I first published in the Journal of Heredity, you see.
But I also published in the...
American Sideround Production, 1934, somewhere along in there.
That must be the journal, that's the journal.
That's the Journal of Heredity.
Yeah.
Yeah, that's March of 33.
Yeah.
Okay, now here's the Journal of Ophthalmology, December 35.
That's the one that you have there.
And then here's one on the same subject from the
Texas State Journal of Medicine in 37.
That's where you were invited to give the speech.
In Fort Worth.
Fort Worth, uh-huh.
And there's American Society of Animal Production, I guess.
Well, this is from the Proceedings of the American Society of Animal Production.
Yeah, that's 34, right?
Where'd you get all this stuff?
Well, you must have given those either to Mr. Colfer or to Ernest Langford, wasn't it?
I gave it to Ernest Langford, yeah.
I remember now he asked me for all that stuff.
Mm-hmm.
And then I have... What does that one mean?
That's a clipping from the Eagle in 1960.
It is.
Uh-huh.
And that's about you and some of your work and somebody from the University of Cincinnati by the name of Workany, A-R-K-A-N-Y.
Yeah, he also... You see, when...
When this came out, a lot of these other schools started projects of their own, and he took up rats.
And he tried on other vitamins, I think B1 or something.
And so Warneke gave us credit for starting a lot of tests for other schools like that.
And he mentioned somewhere in the article, I don't know who wrote the article, I imagine somebody in here took it.
at school and said something about that you had letters from a lot of people who either questioned your results.
I only had one who questioned it.
Most scientists won't do that, you see.
Well, most of them, I guess, were corroborating your work and praising you for it.
Yeah, they were.
But you know it doesn't pay to say something isn't so anymore.
No, it really doesn't.
I want to show you
Here's a book written by...
Nutrition and Physical Regeneration by Price, and he got our work in there, see there?
He starts in there.
One thing about it that they can't take away, A&M College gets credit for starting this kind of work.
And that's what pleases me, A&M College.
I think a lot of A&M.
Well, that means a whole lot more than you know than me.
Well, I think that in your time, you were talking earlier about some of the other people who were here, like Dean Pereira and Dr. Francis and so forth, and I think that
Although I never met them, I had the idea, perhaps, that they had a lot of same feelings that you did, that they put the college before themselves.
Well, that's what I'd like to do.
Now, there's that exhibit at Fort Worth there.
Oh, this is when you gave us the speech.
Now, if I didn't give Langford one of them, you can put that in your folder.
No, I don't have one of those.
You want that?
Now, is this the one that, is this the article you got?
I believe it is, yeah.
Same one.
Right.
Yeah.
I'll tell you,
Did you have one of these?
No, I do not.
I would like very much to have one of those.
Well, you can have this one.
Okay.
Now, I've written on, since this was written, they awarded me this title of fella.
You haven't got anything on that either.
Yeah, I have a clipping on that, 63.
Yeah.
Yeah.
Uh-huh.
That was the American Society of Animal Science that awarded you the honorary medal.
Yes.
Uh-huh.
Have you got about the honorary member of the Saturn Swirling Club here, the X-ray man?
I'll just put it down there.
No.
Well, here.
You haven't got one of these, have you?
Saturn Swirling Club?
I have some of them.
I'm not sure they have that one.
This is a...
was kind of got a little careless and put my name on there.
You must have been one of the early members of that, were you not?
Yes.
I forget right now just exactly when it was started.
Now, here's another.
Do you need anything like this?
This is a bulletin we got on cutting seed mills.
Well, I was going to get around to asking you that sooner or later.
Well, you take this one.
And then here's one on fraud investigations in Texas from 1888 to 1957.
You stick that in here.
Okay.
I think you probably retired before I came so that
I retired in 65.
So I came in 71.
You did?
I haven't had a chance to write you a congratulatory letter upon your retirement as I do now.
When people retire now, I write them a congratulatory letter and I say I'm interested in any of their papers that they have, like any bulletins or articles they've written and things like that.
We have some of yours and we'd be happy to add these others to it.
I think I'll give you some of these letters here.
We haven't talked about this yet, but
In putting rations together, there's a method called Pearson Square.
I don't know whether you ever heard of it or not.
No.
But Dierman used it a whole lot.
But it's the editing thing called Pearson Square.
Say you wanted to make a 15% ration and put that in the square, and you're going to use a grain that has 10% crude protein, and this is crude protein.
And you've got a supplement that has 60% crude protein like tannocates.
Now, what you do is, for this to work, one of these corners has got to be smaller than this, and one's got to be larger than this.
Now, how much grain and supplement do you put together to get this?
See, that's the question.
And this method here is called Pearson Square.
Well, this and that's 45.
And this and that's five.
So that makes 50, but you want 100 pounds, say, so you multiply it by two.
This will go in 102.
It'll be 90 pounds of grain and 10 pounds of supper.
Well, now, how do you know that'll work?
Well, 10% of 90 is nine, and 60% of 10 is six.
That's 15, and you've got 100 pounds.
So, now, I modified that for three feet.
We just used...
Two feet here.
So when I got to teaching, and I dreamed this up.
You've heard of dreams?
Well, I was thinking about it.
I tried and tried and tried to figure out some way to put three feet together by the Pearson Square.
And so one night, about 2.30 in the morning, that came to me.
And I got up right then, because you may forget those things if you don't, and tried it out, and it worked like nobody's business.
Now, here's some letters I got on it.
Yeah, this fellow Bostad was the chairman of the Department of Aluminum at Wisconsin, and that's what he said about it.
It looks to me as if your modification of the Pearson square and mixing feeds is an excellent device for quick and accurate mixing of more than two feeds.
Yeah.
I think of it so well that I am having copies made for you during closure to give to other members of our department to
one or two of our graduate students.
I trust you will publish this.
Now, I thought that was pretty good for a fellow like Wisconsin.
Now, that's another thing that came out of A&M College.
And before I published on that, I wrote Cornell, and I asked the dairy department here if they use it in milk production, taking one fat production of one kind of milk to another.
and change it to another fat content.
But that's only two.
So I wrote around to Derryman.
I wrote to everybody I could think of that would probably be in that field.
And nobody had ever done what we did, you see, on that.
And then I published it.
And that's what he wanted me to do there, you see.
Because he didn't know anything about it either.
Who was Pearson?
Well, he was a mathematician way back.
I think he's from England, Carl Pearson.
He was the one who figured out this Pearson Square for two.
You see, pharmacists can use that.
They've got two solutions to mix and use Pearson Square.
It's wonderful.
So it's kind of a universally accepted formula for a mixture of two ingredients.
But I wanted to mix three.
How did you work it out?
Well, we'd say, well I want a ration, but I want 10% alfalfa meal in my ration.
That'd be the third feature.
Then how do I use this formula for that?
Well, you have a fat meal, it's 20% protein.
So if you're going to mix up, we always do this on a 100-pound basis because then you can go from 100 to a ton or anything.
Well, if you're going to use 10% or 10 pounds, that leaves 90 pounds of these two feeds.
So since you're going to work with 90 pounds, then you can't use this because this is based on 10 pounds.
So you get 9% of that, then you put 9 there, see?
And 9% of this fits 4.
And then, 10 pounds of 25, that's 2 pounds of protein there.
And 2 pounds from this leaves 13, you put in there, see.
Alright, then you go to track it again.
That's 41.
And this is 4.
That's 45.
You want 90.
Which is twice this.
Come in there.
So times 2 equals 82.
Times 2 equals 8.
That gives you 90.
Now, we've got 82 grain times 10% protein.
Go back to this.
That gives you 8.2.
You've got 10 pounds of alfalfa times 20% protein.
That's 2.
You've got 8 pounds of tankage times 6% protein.
That's 4.8.
Now this is a hundred and ten, five, seven, fifteen.
Yeah, and that's what this fellow here liked.
He said, it is, it's really good.
If I got a fellow named Knox in there from Mexico, read what he said about it.
I'm ready to thank you for sending us a copy of A Modification of the Parsons Square and Making Fees.
I've shown it to the professors, to Professors Neal and Watkins, and they've made copies for them.
We all agree that it is an ingenious use of the method and should be quite helpful in calculating formula where definite percentages are required.
See, you can use it for four or five fees either.
All you have to do is subtract that from the other.
Now, why didn't somebody do that before I come along?
Heck, you know, I'm not very smart.
But I stumbled on that, but I dreamed it.
I'd been thinking about it so hard, you know, trying to help these boys.
And...
I was amazed that I couldn't find anybody that had ever done that before.
Well, I would have thought, like you, that perhaps some of the feed companies would have put somebody on to that earlier.
Yes.
I was surprised at that, too.
Now, there's one feed company man in there named Sotolo.
He used to be with Armoring Company.
Is that Satola?
Yeah, that's Satola.
Read his letter now.
He went away into... Would those letters be more valuable to the archives than they would to me?
I don't need them.
Of course, a fellow can make copies of them.
Well, I think they would be very nice to have in the archives.
We'd be pleased to have them.
Maybe I ought to make copies of them and then send them to you.
Okay.
Another question that comes to mind I'd like to ask you.
With all of the research and so forth that you have done in swine, how much were you involved in the evolution of the swine short course?
Well, of course, the swine short course...
had us beginning from the Texas Swine Breeders Association in connection with the head of the department.
And they thought it'd be a good idea to have a swine short course.
And I think that later developed, whereas they have some of these courses out in the state.
I know the Texas Swine Breeders Association, they don't call it that anymore.
I think they call it Texas Pork Producers Association.
Porkus, P-O-R-C-U-S is a Latin word meaning pig.
But I don't know why they changed it from Texas Swine Breeders to Texas Pork Producers.
I guess they thought pork was a little nicer name than swine.
But the Texas Swine Breeders Association was organized in 1890, and they used to have two meetings a year.
They called them...
for both of them were so-called educational meeting like short course.
But they had one out in the state and one here.
That made it nice.
Sometimes they'd have one at Plainview, sometimes they'd have one at San Antonio, and the other one always here.
And it made it real nice for the swine breeders.
When they had it out in the state, they could visit farms, hog farms and stuff like that, and they could also have
related industries like lumber yards, hardware stores, feed companies, and the press come to those meetings to see and they were all interested.
So all I did, I didn't do anything, all I did is they put me on the program, I wrote a paper.
Well, that was in itself a substantial contribution considering the amount of work you had already done in swine research.
That's what I want to say, I guess.
Well, swine is made up of five sections.
Breeding, feeding, sanitation and disease, marketing, and general management.
And your research
can enter any one of those areas.
And I always thought when a fellow asked me a question that I couldn't, didn't know the answer of or couldn't go to the literature and find the answer, that that's the problem.
And that's how we get some of our problems to do all the research.
If we can get the answer out of the literature, the course on that cotton seed meal,
I could get the answer out of there, but it wasn't the right answer, you see.
Or it wasn't a satisfactory answer.

Well, after I'd gone through the literature and found out that they made those statements on 30% coccineal ration, somehow I know that hit me that that shouldn't be that way or something and got me to thinking a little bit on it.
And another thing we did that I think is quite vital to research is...
I hadn't been here too long, about four years, until I quit putting, usually when they try out a ration, they put ten pigs in this lot and ten pigs in that lot and so on, and feed them as a group.
Well, I finally decided after four or five years that you didn't know how much feed each pig was eating.
So I talked to the director and gave us enough money to build some individual feeding pens.
We built 80 individual feeding pens out of 100.
at the old station.
And we fed our pigs individually.
You take on this gospel, if you don't feed them individually, you don't know how much gospel killed a pig or you didn't know how much feed he ate.
And that, I think, is one of our contributions to research.
And we did another thing.
When I came here, the government put out a bulletin
on how to conduct research with animals.
And they had you to weigh them three days at the beginning and three days at the end of your test to get the initial weight and final weight.
Well I did that for about from 25 to 30 some odd and decided I wasn't getting anywhere there.
It looks to me like one weight was just as good because three weights
That second weight, you've already handled the pig some.
He may have interfered with his gain or something.
Third weight, he interfered with his gain.
And it wasn't a true weight.
And they said to take the second weight, the middle weight, to start your test on.
Well, then the next day, if a pig had been getting corn, you put him on oats, and he wasn't used to eating oats.
He's not going to eat what he should.
He's not going to gain so much.
So I just decided we'd get a test going.
to see if it paid to weigh three days or over one day.
And we published that, too.
And I don't know whether you got a copy of that or not.
One-day weight against three-day weights, we published that in the American Sidewound Production.
And then that was 10 years later.
We published in 1936.
In 1946, a guy up at Illinois decided
try to verify our work or disprove it or something.
And he came to the same conclusions.
That one day wait would give you just as good a reliable data as three days.
Well, that saved a lot of work.
Yeah.
With that, together with individual feeding, I think it sure helps us out on research.
I would imagine that the amount of work that you and other people working with you did must have done, had a substantial effect on the economy of Texas.
There's a pretty good amount of pork production in Texas, I would think.
Well, there was at that time.
You know, when I came here, we had 500,000 farms in Texas.
Now they tell me they have about 180,000.
Less farms.
Well uh those 500,000 farms each one of them on the average killed about two pigs a year so there's the million pigs that they killed every year just for farm use.
Well with 180,000 farms that that's a substantial decrease but uh yeah of course the old pig he got the name mortgage lifter you know because he
supposed to pay for a lot of mortgage forms.
That's what they call it, mortgage lifting.
I hadn't heard that before.
Corn belt, yeah.
Yeah, he's known as the mortgage lifter.
But if you can reduce the cost of the rations by proper use of cotton seed meal, you have improved the profit margin.
And by...

use of and also you of course not only you reduced the cost of the rations but you increase the quantity of them that reach maturity and also the same thing by introduction of vitamin A you improve the survival rate or decrease the anytime you can help a product that's produced on the farm uh
It's market value, and you're helping a lot of other industries, too, that pay taxes.
Processors, truckers.
You mentioned that you had these individual pins out on the old station.
Where was... F&B Station up here.
I don't know whether you ever heard of it or not.
No, F&B Station Road, yeah.
Well, it's just right beyond that.
There's still one long building up there.
It's left, they've torn down most of them.
There used to be a silo, they've torn it down.
When did they discontinue the so-called College Station, Experiment Station?
Well, I think they still have some.
They still have some?
Yeah, I think they still have some.
I was uncertain.
We have a lot of the Experiment Station records over in the archives, research project files.
and annual reports of the various individual stations.
Most of the college stations, what you call college stations, of course down there, that farm down there at the river, can end up here.
There used to be quite a bit of work on, most of it was agronomy.
You know, fertilizer testing and variety of crops and stuff like that.
I think they've cut out a lot of that and taken it down yonder.
We have the annual reports of the various stations and so on and so forth, and somehow I've got an impression that the station itself in College Station has been discontinued, but not entirely.
Yeah, I think that's about right.
They probably shifted it around down there.
I think they called this, I forget what station, they called it FB station number 10, I think.
Yeah, they made a lot of changes in that regard.
They hadn't, the research is still going on, but it's just different places.
I believe we talked a little bit ago about that you retired then from teaching and researching in 65.
But you tell me you still have an office here.
Are you still continuing to do some research?
Well, when they made me that, uh, Dr. Butler, head of this department, said I was still a member of the Attaway staff.
And actually in 1970, they asked me to take a course, to teach courses.
They were short a faculty member here.
And I taught feed and feeding over there in 1970 for one term.
But, uh,
I understand the way the thing is set up.
If you're Professor Emeritus, that they will furnish you a space to come and read your journals and take care of your business.
Yeah, that's the way I understand it too.
And they gave me a phone and they were really nice to me.
I wasn't expecting that.
So you're not involved in any individual research projects or anything of that nature anymore.
No.
But you do have an office to which you can come.
That's really nice.
I presume you have some secretarial assistance.
Yes, she'll write a letter for me.
We talked a little bit earlier and looked briefly at an article in which you were made an honorary fellow of the American Society of Animal Science.
I believe in 1965, at the Swine and Shark Course, you were awarded the Royal Order of the Silk and Purse.
Yes.
I've forgotten about that.
What was that?
That was in 1965.
Is that one of those mentioned in that?
No, I don't guess it was.
I've seen that bulletin with my name on the front of it.
Let's see.
I have an article here from the Eagle in 1965.
Oh, does that tell about that?
That tells about that.
Oh, yeah.
You got that?
Did you get other awards?
Well, what's that up there?
I got that award, that map up yonder.
Uh-huh.
And then, of course, these people.
That's from the Texas Swine and the Swine Breeders Association.
Up yonder, yeah.
65, yeah.
And then these people made a sketch of me one time, put it in their magazine, Mold Breeders Who's Who.
Mm-hmm.
But, yeah.
I was invited to judge the swine at the International one time.
I thought this was quite an honor.
So what you did, what your responsibility there was, you judged the animals first and then the teams who... No, this wasn't, this doesn't have anything to do with the team.
Uh-huh.
See, this is judging the livestock.
Livestock that were there for show.
Yeah.
Uh-huh.
And, uh...
That'll be 152.
See, this livestock, they invite different judges to judge it, you see.
And I was judging the Duroc Barrels.
Duroc Barrels, and this was in Chicago.
Uh-huh.
International.
Uh-huh.
Was this, let's see, there's a clip in here.
It says 1939.
That was it.
Well, but that was 1938.
The show was in 38.
So that was, I would imagine, it would be quite an honor to be invited.
Yes, up to that time.
I don't know what's happened since.
They hadn't come down to this far to get a judge in Texas.
They'd stayed up yonners most of the places.
When the student stock judging teams go to the International Livestock Exposition and judge, what what livestock do they judge?
They judge
It's like any judging contest where they have cattle, sheep, hogs, and horses.
Did they judge the stock that is entered in the show?
No, they don't judge that same stock.

The show will go around, and maybe you're an exhibitor there, and if you've got an animal that you don't mind them working on, you'll say, well, you can take my animal, and they'll get them all together like that.
There's usually four animals in a class.
